The Nigerian equities market maintained uptrend as Index surged further by 0.90 per cent into the week, following price appreciation in Dangote Cement, Zenith Bank and Access Bank. The All-Share Index (ASI) increased by 247.25 absolute points, representing a growth of 0.90 per cent to close at 27,586.93 points. Similarly, the overall market capitalisation size gained N117 billion to close at N13.316 trillion. The upturn was impacted by gains recorded in medium and large capitalised stocks, amongst which are; Dangote Cement, Zenith Bank, Presco, Nascon Allied Industries and PZ Cussons Nigeria. Analysts at Afrinvest Limited said that “Following the recent trend in the market, we maintain our bullish outlook on the market this week.” Market breadth closed positive as 26 stocks posted gains while 20 stocks posted declines. Fidson healthcare and PZ Cussons Nigeria recorded the highest price gain of 9.80 per cent each, to close at N2.80 and N5.60, respectively, while Unity Bank followed with a gain 9.59 per cent to close at 80 kobo, per share. Consolidated Hallmark Insurance went up by 9.09 per cent to close at 36 kobo, while Cornerstone Insurance appreciated by 8.62 per cent each, to close at 63 kobo, per share. On the other hand, NCR Nigeria led the losers’ chart by 10 per cent, to close at N4.05, per share. Livestock Feeds followed with a decline of eight per cent to close at 46 kobo, while Courteville Business Solutions went down by 7.69 to close at 24 kobo, per share.  Forte Oil lost 6.11 per cent to close at N16.90, while Jaiz Bank shed 4.41 per cent to close at 65 kobo, per share. However, the total volume traded declined by 14.23 per cent to 446.38 million shares, worth N5.82 billion, and traded in 5,727 deals. Transactions in the shares of United Bank for Africa (UBA) topped the activity chart with 86.78 million shares valued at N709.37 million. Zenith Bank followed with 73.21 million shares worth N1.51 billion, while FBN Holdings traded 34.72 million shares valued at N240.98 million. Access Bank traded 27.44 million shares valued at N297.39 million, while FCMB Group transacted 23.71 million shares worth N48.898 million.